\newlabel{tab:method_comparison_scope}{{1}{3}{Comparison of concept erasure methods by implementation status and role in this work. We distinguish between methods implemented in this repository and those positioned as literature baselines}{table.1}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Representative completed paper-run comparisons at layer 8, $\lambda =1.0$. Columns T (tangent-constrained) and A (ambient baseline) compare two erasure methods. Utility metrics are task-specific: answer-matching delta for sycophancy, helpfulness delta for safety, and profession control accuracy for Bias in Bios. Leakage and displacement decrease from left to right (lower is better); utility increases from left to right (higher is better). This table reports single completed run points, not exhaustive sweeps; layer-4 analogues exist in the same experimental series. Tangent erasure achieves substantially lower leakage across all three domains but requires higher displacement and produces sharper utility drops.}}{3}{table.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:completed_results_summary}{{2}{3}{Representative completed paper-run comparisons at layer 8, $\lambda =1.0$. Columns T (tangent-constrained) and A (ambient baseline) compare two erasure methods. Utility metrics are task-specific: answer-matching delta for sycophancy, helpfulness delta for safety, and profession control accuracy for Bias in Bios. Leakage and displacement decrease from left to right (lower is better); utility increases from left to right (higher is better). This table reports single completed run points, not exhaustive sweeps; layer-4 analogues exist in the same experimental series. Tangent erasure achieves substantially lower leakage across all three domains but requires higher displacement and produces sharper utility drops}{table.2}{}}
